```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <map>

int main() {
    std::ifstream file("input.txt");
    std::string line;

    // Create a map to store the count of each word
    std::map<std::string, int> word_count;

    // Read each line from the file and count the occurrences of the word
    while (std::getline(file, line)) {
        std::istringstream iss(line);
        std::string word;
        int count = 0;

        while (iss >> word) {
            if (word == "specific_word") {
                count++;
            }
        }

        word_count["specific_word"] += count;
    }

    // Print the count of the word
    std::cout << "The word 'specific_word' occurs " << word_count["specific_word"] << " times in the file." << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

In this program, we first include the necessary headers for input/output, string manipulation, and maps. Then, we declare a map to store the count of each word.

Next, we open the input file and read each line. For each line, we create an istream to parse the line into words, and we increment a counter for each occurrence of the specific word. Finally, we add the count to the map and print the count at the end.

Note that you'll need to replace "specific_word" with the specific word you want to count. Also, make sure that the input file exists and is in the same directory as the program.
